==Discography==
On June 10, 2008, Griffin released a comedy CD titled ''[[For Your Consideration (album)|For Your Consideration]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/07/04/PKQ611F0UE.DTL |title=Can't get Enough of Kathy Griffin |last=Adolphson |first=Sue |date=July 6, 2008 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher=Frank J. Vega |page=N12 | access-date=July 8, 2008}}</ref> It is Griffin's first audio-only release of her stand-up material.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} The disc was recorded at the ETK Theatre at the Grand Theatre Center For The Arts in [[Tracy, California]] on February 17, 2008.<ref name="AZ-daily-star">{{cite news|url=http://www.azstarnet.com/sn/aznightbuzz/246178.php|title=An A-List Comedy Release|first=Cathalena E.|last=Burch|date=July 3, 2008|work=[[Arizona Daily Star]]|publisher=John M. Humenik|access-date=July 8, 2008|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221141205/http://www.azstarnet.com/sn/aznightbuzz/246178.php|archivedate=December 21, 2008}}</ref> Included on the disc are her takes on various celebrities and her personal life. Griffin stated that she decided to release this CD to try to win a [[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album|Grammy award]].<ref name="AZ-daily-star"/> On December 3, 2008, Griffin was nominated for a Grammy for Best Comedy Album. However, she lost to [[George Carlin]]'s ''[[It's Bad for Ya]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}

On August 25, 2009, Griffin released a second comedy album, ''[[Suckin' It for the Holidays]]'', in another bid for a Grammy. The album was initially released as a digital download and retail released on November 3, 2009. Despite the album's holiday title, it contains little holiday-related content, and it just barely made the nominations cut-off.<ref name="Celebrity News Service">{{cite news|url=http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7016265566?Kathy%20Griffin%20Baits%20Grammy%20Voters%20With%20Second%20Comedy%20Album|title=Kathy Griffin Baits Grammy Voters With Second Comedy Album|first=Anthony|last=Jones|date=September 1, 2009|work=[[Celebrity News Service]]|publisher=AHN Media Corporation|access-date=September 5, 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904023612/http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7016265566?Kathy%20Griffin%20Baits%20Grammy%20Voters%20With%20Second%20Comedy%20Album|archivedate=September 4, 2009}}</ref> On December 2, 2009 it was nominated for Best Comedy Album, making it Griffin's second Grammy nomination.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}

Griffin received her third Grammy nomination for ''[[Does the Bible Belt|Kathy Griffin: Does the Bible Belt]]'' in 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.com/news/ci_16759537?source=pkg|title=2011 Grammy Awards – complete list of nominees|date=December 2, 2010|access-date=December 2, 2010|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|publisher=MediaNews Group|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207175339/http://www.dailynews.com/news/ci_16759537?source=pkg|archivedate=December 7, 2010}}</ref> and her fourth in 2011 for ''[[50 and Not Pregnant|Kathy Griffin: 50 And Not Pregnant]]''.

On May 4, 2012, the full length version of "[[I'll Say It]]", the theme song of her show ''[[Kathy (TV series)|Kathy]]'', was released to iTunes as a single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/ill-say-it-single/id536395438|title="I'll Say It" on iTunes}}</ref>
On August 20, 2012, Griffin released a seven-track EP containing dance remixes of "I'll Say It".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/ill-say-it-remixes/id553482043|title="I'll Say It - Remixes" on iTunes}}</ref>

On August 14, 2014, Griffin released a third comedy CD titled ''[[Look at My Butt Crack]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}

